Fix AOT compatibility warnings in the ManagedServiceIdentity.Serialization.cs file at `/tmp/sv-2e1572690bd34a58abb7501073088ffb/before/Common/Custom/Models/ManagedServiceIdentity.Serialization.cs`.

This file has 4 `JsonSerializer` calls that need to be replaced with AOT-safe alternatives.

### Context about the types:

`ManagedServiceIdentityType` is a readonly struct with a `[JsonConverter(typeof(ManagedServiceIdentityTypeConverter))]`. The converter's Write method writes `"type": "<value>"` (property name + value). Its Read method reads an object `{"type":"<value>"}` and returns `new ManagedServiceIdentityType(value)`.

The `Write` method has signature: `internal void Write(Utf8JsonWriter writer, ModelReaderWriterOptions options, JsonSerializerOptions jOptions = null)`

The `jOptions` parameter is used to pass alternative JsonSerializerOptions (like a V3 converter). When jOptions is null (which is the IJsonModel path), we should inline the default behavior. When jOptions is non-null, we need to get the converter from the options and call it directly.

### Changes needed:

**Line 31:** Replace:
```csharp
            JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions);
```
With:
```csharp
            if (jOptions != null)
            {
                var converter = (JsonConverter<ManagedServiceIdentityType>)jOptions.GetConverter(typeof(ManagedServiceIdentityType));
                converter.Write(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions);
            }
            else
            {
                writer.WritePropertyName("type"u8);
                writer.WriteStringValue(ManagedServiceIdentityType.ToString());
            }
```

**Line 49:** Replace:
```csharp
                    JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, item.Value, jOptions);
```
With:
```csharp
                    writer.WriteObjectValue(item.Value, options);
```
(`options` here is the `ModelReaderWriterOptions options` parameter available in scope. `WriteObjectValue` is an extension method on `Utf8JsonWriter` that handles IJsonModel types correctly.)

**Line 206:** Replace:
```csharp
                    type = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<ManagedServiceIdentityType>($"{{{property}}}");
```
With:
```csharp
                    if (jOptions != null)
                    {
                        var typeConverter = (JsonConverter<ManagedServiceIdentityType>)jOptions.GetConverter(typeof(ManagedServiceIdentityType));
                        var typeBytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes($"{{{property}}}");
                        var typeReader = new Utf8JsonReader(typeBytes);
                        typeReader.Read();
                        type = typeConverter.Read(ref typeReader, typeof(ManagedServiceIdentityType), jOptions);
                    }
                    else
                    {
                        type = new ManagedServiceIdentityType(property.Value.GetString());
                    }
```

**Line 218:** Replace:
```csharp
                        dictionary.Add(new ResourceIdentifier(property0.Name), JsonSerializer.Deserialize<UserAssignedIdentity>(property0.Value.GetRawText()));
```
With:
```csharp
                        dictionary.Add(new ResourceIdentifier(property0.Name), UserAssignedIdentity.DeserializeUserAssignedIdentity(property0.Value));
```

Also add `using System.Text.Json.Serialization;` if not already present (for `JsonConverter<T>` type).

